W-A-F and Firewall Manager.

W-A-F, the Web Application Firewall, is a Layer seven filter for H-T-T-P and H-T-T-P-S traffic. It inspects requests against rules you define and either allows, blocks, counts, or CAPTCHA-challenges them before they reach your application. It attaches to CloudFront, where the rules run globally at the edge, to Application Load Balancer, to A-P-I Gateway, to AppSync for GraphQL A-P-Is, and to Cognito User Pools.

The top-level resource is a Web A-C-L, a container of rules with a default action, allow or block, for requests that match nothing. Rules are evaluated in priority order and the first matching rule wins. The rule types are worth knowing: an I-P set matches specific I-Ps or C-I-D-R ranges; a geo-match rule matches by country; a rate-based rule blocks any I-P exceeding a threshold over a five-minute window; string and regex rules match the U-R-I, query string, headers, or body; and there are dedicated S-Q-L-injection and cross-site-scripting rules for those attack patterns. On top of your own rules, Managed Rule Groups are pre-built, A-W-S- or vendor-maintained rule sets, the Core Rule Set, Known Bad Inputs, and Bot Control, so you get broad coverage without hand-writing anything.

Firewall Manager centralises security policy across an entire A-W-S Organisation, W-A-F Web A-C-Ls, Shield Advanced subscriptions, security-group baselines, Network Firewall, and Route 53 D-N-S Firewall rules. You define a policy once in the management or delegated-administrator account and Firewall Manager applies and enforces it across every member account. The two practical patterns are enforcing a baseline, say every internet-facing A-L-B must have the Core Rule Set attached, and auto-onboarding, where a new account joining the Organisation inherits every policy on day one. The cue is clear: apply W-A-F or Shield across all accounts, or new accounts must inherit automatically, means Firewall Manager.
